Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1 & 2. Guard Navigation with a Confirmation Dialog

In your `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is **required** for async checks — without it, navigation completes before your `await` returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".

## 3. Custom "Cancel" Back Button

In `EditProductPage.xaml`, attach a `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so your guard still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Since `GoToAsync("..")` triggers a `Pop`, your `OnNavigating` guard will intercept it and show the dialog before actually leaving.

**Summary:** `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the arrow with "Cancel", and `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()` gives you an async confirmation gate that works for both the custom button and the system back gesture.
